{
  "chapter_number": 8,
  "chapter_title": "Arrays in C",
  "sections": [
    {
      "section_title": "Introduction",
      "keywords": ["arrays"],
      "content": "An array is a collection of elements of the same data type stored in contiguous memory locations."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "What is an Array?",
      "keywords": ["definition"],
      "content": "An array is a data structure used to store multiple values of the same type under a single name."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Need for Arrays",
      "keywords": ["need"],
      "content": "Arrays eliminate the need for multiple variables when storing similar types of data."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Advantages of Arrays",
      "keywords": ["advantages"],
      "content": [
        "Easy data management",
        "Fast access using indexes",
        "Efficient memory utilization",
        "Simplifies programming"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Declaration of Array",
      "keywords": ["declaration"],
      "content": "data_type array_name[size];"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Example Declaration",
      "keywords": ["example"],
      "content": [
        "int marks[5];",
        "float salary[10];",
        "char grade[20];"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Initialization of Array",
      "keywords": ["initialization"],
      "content": "int arr[5]={10,20,30,40,50};"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Array Indexing",
      "keywords": ["index"],
      "content": "Array indexing starts from 0. The first element is stored at index 0."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Accessing Array Elements",
      "keywords": ["accessing elements"],
      "content": "Elements are accessed using index values such as arr[0], arr[1], arr[2]."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Types of Arrays",
      "keywords": ["types"],
      "content": [
        "One Dimensional Array",
        "Two Dimensional Array",
        "Multi Dimensional Array"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "One Dimensional Array",
      "keywords": ["1d array"],
      "content": "A one-dimensional array stores data in a single row."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Two Dimensional Array",
      "keywords": ["2d array"],
      "content": "A two-dimensional array stores data in rows and columns."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Syntax of Two Dimensional Array",
      "keywords": ["2d syntax"],
      "content": "int matrix[3][3];"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Array Traversal",
      "keywords": ["traversal"],
      "content": "Traversal means accessing every element of the array one by one."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Limitations of Arrays",
      "keywords": ["limitations"],
      "content": [
        "Fixed size",
        "Insertion and deletion are difficult",
        "Can store only same data type elements"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Example Program",
      "keywords": ["program"],
      "content": "#include <stdio.h>\n\nint main()\n{\n int arr[5]={10,20,30,40,50};\n printf(\"%d\",arr[0]);\n return 0;\n}"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Applications",
      "keywords": ["applications"],
      "content": [
        "Student Records",
        "Matrix Operations",
        "Searching Algorithms",
        "Sorting Algorithms",
        "Data Storage"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "summary": [
    "Arrays store multiple values of the same data type.",
    "Array indexing starts from 0.",
    "Arrays provide fast element access.",
    "Arrays can be one-dimensional or multidimensional.",
    "Arrays have fixed size limitations."
  ]
}
